section.introduction:
Recall that an m \times n matrix A is a rectangular array of real numbers with m rows and n columns,

    A = \begin{bmatrix}
    a_{11} \amp a_{12} \amp \dots \amp a_{1n} \\
    a_{21} \amp a_{22} \amp \dots \amp a_{2n} \\
    \vdots \amp \vdots \amp \ddots \amp \vdots \\
    a_{m1} \amp a_{n2} \amp \dots \amp a_{mn}
    \end{bmatrix}

The jth column of A is the column vector \vec{a}_j. Then, the matrix can be written as,

    A = \begin{bmatrix} \vec{a}_1 \amp \cdots \amp \vec{a}_n \end{bmatrix}

The arithmetic of vectors naturally extends to the more general matrices. Recall that a vector can be thought of as a particular type of matrix.

subsection.definition:
Scalar multiplication
Let A be an m \times n matrix, k \in \mathbb{R} be a scalar. Then, kA is the matrix formed by multiplying each of the entries of A by k, or,

    \boxed{(kA)_{ij} = kA_{ij}}

ul.li:
Proof of 1. for 2 \times 2 matrices. Let A = \begin{bmatrix} a \amp b \\ c \amp d \end{bmatrix}, B = \begin{bmatrix} e \amp f \\ g \amp h \end{bmatrix}. Then,

                    r(A + B) = r \begin{bmatrix} a + e \amp b + f \\ c + g \amp d + h \end{bmatrix} \amp = \begin{bmatrix} r(a + e) \amp r(b + f) \\ r(c + g) \amp r(d + h) \end{bmatrix}
                    \amp = \begin{bmatrix} ra + re \amp rb + rf \\ rc + rg \amp rd + rh \end{bmatrix}
                    \amp = \begin{bmatrix} ra \amp rb \\ rc \amp rd \end{bmatrix} + \begin{bmatrix} re \amp rf \\ rg \amp rh \end{bmatrix}
                    \amp = r A + r B
